TY  - JOUR
AU  - Huang, Jing-Zhi
AU  - Liu, Bibo
AU  - Shi, Zhan
T1  - Determinants of Short-Term Corporate Yield Spreads: Evidence from the Commercial Paper Market*
PY  - 2023
Y1  - 2023/03/01
DO  - 10.1093/rof/rfac030
JO  - Review of Finance
JA  - Rev Financ
VL  - 27
IS  - 2
SP  - 539
EP  - 579
SN  - 1572-3097
AB  - What drives short-term credit spreads: credit risk, liquidity risk, or both? We investigate this issue using the structural approach to credit risk modeling and a novel data set of secondary market transaction prices for Chinese commercial papers (CPs). In particular, we propose and test a structural model with jump risk and exogenous market illiquidity under which the predicted yield spreads can be decomposed into a credit component and a liquidity component. We find that credit risk and, especially liquidity risk, are important determinants of short-term yield spreads. Our model-based decomposition results show that, on average, credit risk and market liquidity account for about 25% and 52% of CP yield spreads, respectively. For comparison, we also examine the drivers of the US CP yield spreads using security-level data. We find that credit risk accounts for a small fraction of the observed yield spreads but liquidity contributes a much greater proportion.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rof/rfac030
ER  - 



